    cellular: "Neonatal respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) results from surfactant deficiency in premature infants. Ground glass opacity on CXR with air bronchograms. Treatment: CPAP (first-line for mild-moderate), surfactant replacement therapy (via ETT or LISA/MIST technique), and mechanical ventilation for severe cases. Gentle ventilation strategies: target SpO2 90-95% for preterm, avoid excessive tidal volumes, tolerate mild hypercapnia. Bronchopulmonary dysplasia (BPD): chronic lung disease of prematurity from prolonged mechanical ventilation and oxygen therapy. Other neonatal respiratory conditions: transient tachypnea of newborn (TTN), meconium aspiration syndrome (MAS), persistent pulmonary hypertension (PPHN), and congenital diaphragmatic hernia (CDH).",
