    cellular: "Pediatric respiratory anatomy differs: proportionally larger tongue, higher larynx (C3-C4 vs C4-C5 adult), funnel-shaped airway with narrowest point at cricoid (vs glottis in adults), shorter trachea, and more compliant chest wall. Common pediatric conditions: croup (viral, barking cough, stridor -- racemic epinephrine 2.25% nebulized, dexamethasone), bronchiolitis (RSV, supportive care, suctioning, consider HFNC), pneumonia, and foreign body aspiration. Ventilation differences: higher respiratory rates, smaller tidal volumes, uncuffed ETT for some ages (cuffed acceptable with pressure monitoring), and weight-based medication dosing. Pediatric BLS: 15:2 compression-to-ventilation ratio for 2-rescuer.",
